The end of e-tolls is seemingly nigh as the SA National Roads Agency (Sanral) has stopped issuing summonses to non-paying motorists and its collection contract with the Electronic Toll Collections (ETC) comes to an end this month with no new service provider appointed. The contentious Administrative Adjudication of Road Traffic Offences (Aarto) Act on which e-toll fees collection were entirely reliant, according to the Justice Project SA, is also facing legal action that could result in sections of the Act set aside as unconstitutional. It is set to come into effect in June. Government is yet to make an announcement...